      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm stuck on a section of my dissertation. I have a result where the p-value came out to 0.06. My advisor is being really strict about it not being \"statistically significant\" because it's above the 0.05 threshold, but it looks like there is a definite trend in the data. Can you explain the mathematical reasoning behind why we can't just call this significant, even if the trend looks real?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A p-value of 0.06, being above the conventional 0.05 threshold, means your data is not quite strong enough to *conclusively* reject the null hypothesis. It doesn't mean the trend isn't real, though, just that the evidence isn't quite enough to make the decision in the eyes of the strict alpha-level. Think of it like this: you're trying to catch a specific type of small, sneaky creature, and your net only caught a few stragglers.\n\nThe mathematical reasoning boils down to the probability of observing your data (or something more extreme) *if the null hypothesis were actually true*. A p-value of 0.06 means there is a 6% chance you'd see this result purely by random chance, even if there's no actual effect. Since 6% is higher than the 5% risk you've set for yourself (your significance level), you stick with the null hypothesis.\n\nHowever, don't let that scare you into thinking the trend is worthless! A trend is just a sign that something *might* be happening, and you have a few other ways to frame it. You could mention",
      "source": "target",
